Now I have all the context needed. Here's how to build your MCP server:

---

### **Tool Class — `WeatherTools.cs`**

```csharp
using ModelContextProtocol.Server;
using System.ComponentModel;
using System.Text.Json;

[McpServerToolType]
public class WeatherTools(HttpClient httpClient, ILogger<WeatherTools> logger)
{
    [McpServerTool, Description("Get current weather for a city.")]
    public async Task<string> GetWeather(
        [Description("City name, e.g. 'London'")] string city,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        logger.LogInformation("Fetching weather for {City}", city);
        var response = await httpClient.GetStringAsync(
            $"/v1/current.json?q={Uri.EscapeDataString(city)}", cancellationToken);
        return response;
    }

    [McpServerTool, Description("Get 3-day weather forecast for a city.")]
    public async Task<string> GetForecast(
        [Description("City name")] string city,
        [Description("Number of days (1-3)")] int days = 3,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        var response = await httpClient.GetStringAsync(
            $"/v1/forecast.json?q={Uri.EscapeDataString(city)}&days={days}",
            cancellationToken);
        return response;
    }
}
```

### **`Program.cs` — stdio transport**

```csharp
using Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Logging;
using ModelContextProtocol.Server;

var builder = Host.CreateApplicationBuilder(args);

// CRITICAL: log to stderr only — stdout is the JSON-RPC transport
builder.Logging.AddConsole(options =>
    options.LogToStandardErrorThreshold = LogLevel.Trace);

// Register HttpClient with a base address for your API
builder.Services.AddHttpClient<WeatherTools>(client =>
{
    client.BaseAddress = new Uri("https://api.weatherapi.com");
});

builder.Services.AddMcpServer()
    .WithStdioServerTransport()
    .WithToolsFromAssembly();  // discovers all [McpServerToolType] classes

await builder.Build().RunAsync();
```

---

### **How DI works for MCP tools**

The SDK supports two injection styles:

| Style | How it works |
|-------|-------------|
| **Constructor injection** (non-static class) | Services like `HttpClient`, `ILogger<T>` are injected via primary constructor. The class is resolved from DI each invocation. |
| **Method parameter injection** (static class) | DI services appear as method parameters alongside tool parameters. |

**Key rule:** The SDK automatically distinguishes DI services from tool parameters. Types registered in DI (`HttpClient`, `ILogger<T>`, `CancellationToken`, `IMcpServer`, `IProgress<>`) are **injected at runtime** and **never appear** in the tool's JSON schema exposed to the LLM. Only parameters with `[Description]` are visible to the LLM.

In the example above, `WeatherTools` uses **constructor injection** — `HttpClient` and `ILogger<WeatherTools>` are injected by the DI container. The LLM only sees `city` and `days` as callable parameters.

To scaffold this project from scratch:

```bash
dotnet new mcpserver -n WeatherMcpServer
cd WeatherMcpServer
dotnet build && dotnet run
```
